Software architecture refers to the high-level structure of a software system.
System Design is about designing the entire system — not just software — to meet scalability, reliability and performance requirements.
Heap memory is logically contiguous but physically non-contiguous.
Heap is a region of a process’s address space used for dynamic memory allocation.
Audit Log and Activity Log are both used to track actions within systems, but they serve different purposes.

Objects do not create other objects on which they relay to do their work, instead they get the objects that they need from an outside world.
Abstraction is separation of interface from implementation so that we can have one interface and many implementations or usages.
Abstract data type: what operations can be performed on this data, ignoring how those operations will be performed.
High level modules should not depend on low level modules rather both should depends on abstraction.
Polymorphism is the ability of a variable, function or object to take on multiple forms.
Interface defines what a class does but not how it does it.
Advantages of generics: compile-time type safety, avoids class cast exceptions and eliminate the need for most type conversions.
Try-catch promotes separation of concern principles by avoiding mixing of business logic code and error handling code.
Volatile ensures that all the threads sees the same value of a variale at any given time.
There is one-to-one mapping between JVM platform threads and OS threads.
Cached shared data causes a thread not to notice that data has been changed by the another thread.
Returned value is wrapped into the Future object, which is returned immediately.
Method get blocks invoking thread until timeout or when the value within the Future object becomes available.
Method wait puts a thread into waiting state against specific monitor.
Any number of threads can be waiting against the same monitor.
Keyword synchronized enforces exclusive access to the block of code.
Creating platform threads is expensive both in terms of time and space.
Thread does not have to block on anthing for the final result of the pipeline to be relevant.
Use IntStream instead of Stream<Integer> when possible.
Interrupts are co-operation mechanism for one thread to tell other thread to stop its execution.
Simply put, calling wait() forces the current thread to wait until some other thread invokes notify() or notifyAll() on the same object.
